{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.3","generated_at":"2026-04-29T16:26:02.011781+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 44 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 57 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":57,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":44,"completed_with_unit_data":44,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"v2.2":6,"v2.1":17,"v2.0":21},"missing_data_jsons":["2001","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2015","2016","2017","2018","2019","2021","2022"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2916,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 44 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -29.2%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":327,"p25":-0.508,"median":-0.2916,"p75":-0.0839},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.0438,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 44 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +4.4%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":44,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":44,"min":-0.3361,"max":1.0927,"mean":0.0842,"median":0.0438,"p25":-0.1065,"p50":0.0438,"p75":0.2114,"p10":-0.2081,"p90":0.3403},"median_actual_dollars":202976.875},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~116 hours per plumbing unit","value":116.1347,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 116.1 hrs/unit (P25 97, P75 139). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 97 and 139 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":44,"min":57.375,"max":354.3341,"mean":122.0086,"median":116.1347,"p25":96.8721,"p50":116.1347,"p75":138.896,"p10":74.0738,"p90":155.1185,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 40.3%","value":0.4027,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 40.3%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":44,"p25":0.3334,"median":0.4027,"p75":0.4616},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$39.67/hr (1.44\u00d7 blended)","value":39.6746,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $39.67/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.44\u00d7 means OWP carries ~44% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":27.485,"loaded_wage_median":39.6746,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4431},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-15.7% median)","value":-0.1572,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -15.7%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":415,"min":-0.9914,"max":3.4135,"mean":-0.0917,"median":-0.1572,"p25":-0.4131,"p50":-0.1572,"p75":0.0876,"p10":-0.5902,"p90":0.3579},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":44,"min":57.375,"max":354.3341,"mean":122.0086,"median":116.1347,"p25":96.8721,"p50":116.1347,"p75":138.896,"p10":74.0738,"p90":155.1185,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":44,"min":1419.3979,"max":11628.9416,"mean":3382.2743,"median":3302.7455,"p25":2556.516,"p50":3302.7455,"p75":3995.0259,"p10":1920.5024,"p90":4225.8609,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":44,"min":1219.6971,"max":9672.2479,"mean":3350.1957,"median":3272.9099,"p25":2721.7967,"p50":3272.9099,"p75":3961.4084,"p10":1940.0059,"p90":4350.3113,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":44,"min":7181.5,"max":41985.5421,"mean":14883.8033,"median":14182.2591,"p25":11389.7809,"p50":14182.2591,"p75":16969.9937,"p10":9320.5022,"p90":18671.5617,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"labor_pct_of_revenue":{"n":44,"min":0.1089,"max":0.3355,"mean":0.2276,"median":0.2241,"p25":0.2047,"p50":0.2241,"p75":0.2547,"p10":0.1849,"p90":0.2786,"note":"Labor cost / revenue","unit":"fraction"},"material_pct_of_revenue":{"n":44,"min":0.0936,"max":0.3135,"mean":0.2268,"median":0.2292,"p25":0.206,"p50":0.229